<subSubSection id="6CE1BECA295BFFE72F64FC2E8228583F" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="description">
<paragraph id="2444ED41295BFFE72F64FC2E8228583F" blockId="3.[794,1419,922,1875]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis id="168F3153295BFFE72F64FC2E84B65CDF" bold="true" box="[794,959,922,947]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Redescription</emphasis>
(mostly translation from 
<bibRefCitation id="406A90B0295BFFE7296EFC2E84B95CBF" author="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M." pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="83 - 90" refId="ref5344" refString="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M. 2010. Novas especies, nova sinonimia e novo registro em Cerambycidae (Coleoptera) do Mexico e da America do Sul. Papeis Avulsos de Zoologia, 50 (7): 83 - 90." type="journal article" year="2010">Martins &amp; Galileo, 2010</bibRefCitation>
): Frons transverse, elevated in relation to the ocular lobes. Frontoclypeal sulcus deep and curved. Median groove very distinct between antennal tubercles. Vertex carinate between antennal tubercles and upper eye lobes. Antennal tubercles close to each oth- er, slightly elevated, rounded at apex. Eyes without setae between ommatidia. Lower eye lobes more distant from each other than insertion of antennae; upper eye lobes more distant from each other than width of one upper lobe. Genae with rounded apex. Antennae in female reaching posterior third of elytra; in male distinctly surpassing elytral apex. Scape subcylindrical, not reaching anterior margin of pronotum. Antennomere III 1/3 longer than IV; IV slightly shorter than V. Prothorax wider than long in both sexes; sides with lateral tubercle from rounded and slightly distinct to more spiniform and distinct; sides with punctures abundant and confluent. Pronotum with large smooth area centrally; remaining dorsal area coarsely punctate, partially confluent, sides coarsely, densely, confluently punctate. Prosternum coarsely rugose-punctate. Scutellum triangular or with rounded apex. Elytra glabrous, with silky appearance, unicolorous; apex rounded, with minute projection at sutural angle (
<specimenCount id="32FD26C8295BFFE72FCAF92E834659DF" box="[948,1103,1690,1715]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="female">three females</specimenCount>
),unarmed in the single male examined. Femora fusiform, with rounded apical projection at inner and outer apices; center of dorsal side of metafemora with long, thick, yellowish setae. Meso- and metatibiae with short spiniform projection at apex. Apex of abdominal ventrite V rounded in both sexes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6CE1BECA295BFFE02F64F8CE8689573F" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="5" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="2444ED41295BFFE02F64F8CE86EE5BBF" blockId="3.[794,1418,1914,2131]" lastBlockId="4.[170,795,218,2131]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="5" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
<emphasis id="168F3153295BFFE72F64F8CE848158FF" bold="true" box="[794,904,1914,1939]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Remarks:</emphasis>
According to 
<bibRefCitation id="406A90B0295BFFE72857F8CE823358FF" author="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M." box="[1065,1338,1914,1939]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" pagination="83 - 90" refId="ref5344" refString="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M. 2010. Novas especies, nova sinonimia e novo registro em Cerambycidae (Coleoptera) do Mexico e da America do Sul. Papeis Avulsos de Zoologia, 50 (7): 83 - 90." type="journal article" year="2010">Martins &amp; Galileo (2010)</bibRefCitation>
(translated): “The presence of the spine at the sides of the prothorax distinguishes 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295BFFE72846F80E836058BF" authority="Nascimento &amp; Santos-Silva &amp; Hernández, 2018" authorityName="Nascimento &amp; Santos-Silva &amp; Hernández" authorityYear="2018" box="[1080,1129,1978,2003]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Iuati" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="168F3153295BFFE72846F80E836058BF" box="[1080,1129,1978,2003]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Iuati</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="0DBC8C28295BFFE72808F80E83ED58BF" box="[1142,1252,1978,2003]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
from all oth- er known genera of Sphallotrichina. By the fusiform metafemora and femora unarmed at apices, it is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295BFFE72F22F7AE8351575F" authority="Bates, 1870" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1870" box="[860,1112,2074,2099]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Butherium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295BFFE72F22F7AE84C4575F" box="[860,973,2074,2099]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Butherium</emphasis>
Bates, 1870
</taxonomicName>
. It differs by the vertex not convex, absence of laterobasal gibbosities on pronotum, pronotal disc with crateriform punctures, scutellum an obtuse triangle, and meso- and metatibiae with short spiniform projection at outer apex. In 
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02EDDFEAE84135E5F" box="[675,794,282,307]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02EDDFEAE841F5E5F" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1870" box="[675,790,282,307]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Butherium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Butherium</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
the vertex is notably convex, pronotum (female) has a rounded gibbosity on each side, the pronotal disc is nearly smooth, scutellum has the shape of an equilateral triangle, and the spiniform projection at outer apex is longer.”With the description of the first male specimen of 
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02CB6FE6E87F75E9F" box="[200,254,474,499]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02CB6FE6E87F35E9F" authorityName="Nascimento &amp; Santos-Silva &amp; Hernández" authorityYear="2018" box="[200,250,474,499]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Iuati" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Iuati</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
we know that the the spiniform lateral tubercle of the prothorax may or may not be present, the shape of the scutellum appears to be very variable, and the vertex (between upper eye lobes and prothorax) is convex as in 
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02D67FDEE86995D1F" box="[281,400,602,627]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02D67FDEE86845D1F" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1870" box="[281,397,602,627]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Butherium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Butherium</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Furthermore, although the center of the pronotum in 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02DF6FDCE86B05DFF" authorityName="Nascimento &amp; Santos-Silva &amp; Hernández" authorityYear="2018" box="[392,441,634,659]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Iuati" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02DF6FDCE86B05DFF" box="[392,441,634,659]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Iuati</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinctly punctate, there are specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02D34FD2E86B25DDF" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1870" box="[330,443,666,691]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Butherium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02D34FD2E86B25DDF" box="[330,443,666,691]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Butherium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with sparse punctures on this area. However, there are differences between 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02ED6FD0E84105DBF" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1870" box="[680,793,698,723]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Butherium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02ED6FD0E84105DBF" box="[680,793,698,723]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Butherium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02CA0FD6E861C5D9F" box="[222,277,730,755]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02CA0FD6E86195D9F" authorityName="Nascimento &amp; Santos-Silva &amp; Hernández" authorityYear="2018" box="[222,272,730,755]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Iuati" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Iuati</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
especially in the distance between antennal tubercles, which are distinctly separated in the former (
<figureCitation id="BCC0F1C4295CFFE02CCFFCAE87F45C5F" box="[177,253,794,819]" captionStart="Figures 7-16" captionStartId="5.[94,162,2042,2067]" captionTargetBox="[132,1379,206,2012]" captionTargetId="figure-1@5.[132,1379,204,2013]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 7-16. (7-15) Iuati spinithorax: (7) Dorsal habitus, male; (8) Ventral habitus, male; (9) Lateral habitus, male; (10) Head, frontal view, male; (11) Head and prothorax, holotype female;(12) Head and prothorax,female 1; (13) Head and prothorax,female 2; (14) Elytron,female 1; (15) Elytron, female 2. (16) Butherium erythropus, head,frontal view,female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5384291" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5384291/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
), and more proximate in the latter (
<figureCitation id="BCC0F1C4295CFFE02EF9FCAE85DD5C5F" box="[647,724,794,819]" captionStart="Figures 7-16" captionStartId="5.[94,162,2042,2067]" captionTargetBox="[132,1379,206,2012]" captionTargetId="figure-1@5.[132,1379,204,2013]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figures 7-16. (7-15) Iuati spinithorax: (7) Dorsal habitus, male; (8) Ventral habitus, male; (9) Lateral habitus, male; (10) Head, frontal view, male; (11) Head and prothorax, holotype female;(12) Head and prothorax,female 1; (13) Head and prothorax,female 2; (14) Elytron,female 1; (15) Elytron, female 2. (16) Butherium erythropus, head,frontal view,female." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5384291" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5384291/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Also, the procoxal cavities in 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02DC2FC8E85245C3F" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1870" box="[444,557,826,851]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Butherium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02DC2FC8E85245C3F" box="[444,557,826,851]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Butherium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are closed or nearly so posteriorly (more distinctly open in 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02E1AFCEE859C5C1F" authorityName="Nascimento &amp; Santos-Silva &amp; Hernández" authorityYear="2018" box="[612,661,858,883]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Iuati" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02E1AFCEE859C5C1F" box="[612,661,858,883]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Iuati</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), laterobasal gibbosities on the pronotum of 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02E4BFCCE85AF5CFF" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1870" box="[565,678,890,915]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Butherium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02E4BFCCE85AF5CFF" box="[565,678,890,915]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Butherium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are much more conspicuous (slightly distinct in 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02E2AFC2E858C5CDF" authorityName="Nascimento &amp; Santos-Silva &amp; Hernández" authorityYear="2018" box="[596,645,922,947]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Iuati" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02E2AFC2E858C5CDF" box="[596,645,922,947]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Iuati</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), protibiae in 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02CD4FC0E86125CBF" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1870" box="[170,283,954,979]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Butherium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02CD4FC0E86125CBF" box="[170,283,954,979]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Butherium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are notably and moderately abruptly widened near apex (slightly and gradually widened in 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02ED7FC6E85D35C9F" authorityName="Nascimento &amp; Santos-Silva &amp; Hernández" authorityYear="2018" box="[681,730,986,1011]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Iuati" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02ED7FC6E85D35C9F" box="[681,730,986,1011]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Iuati</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and the spiniform projection of the outer apex of meso- and metatibiae is longer in 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02DD6FBAE85105B5F" authorityName="Bates" authorityYear="1870" box="[424,537,1050,1075]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Butherium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02DD6FBAE85105B5F" box="[424,537,1050,1075]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Butherium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(shorter in 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02EE9FBAE85C15B5F" authorityName="Nascimento &amp; Santos-Silva &amp; Hernández" authorityYear="2018" box="[663,712,1050,1075]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Iuati" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02EE9FBAE85C15B5F" box="[663,712,1050,1075]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Iuati</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). As for the affirmation that 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02DEBFB8E86CF5B3F" authorityName="Nascimento &amp; Santos-Silva &amp; Hernández" authorityYear="2018" box="[405,454,1082,1107]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Iuati" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02DEBFB8E86CF5B3F" box="[405,454,1082,1107]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Iuati</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only genus with spiniform tubercles at sides of prothorax in Sphallotrichina, this is not true: 
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02D2CFBCE851B5BFF" box="[338,530,1146,1171]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Ochrodiongahani</emphasis>
(Gounelle, 1909), a species questionably included in this genus, has a very conspicuous spiniform tubercle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2444ED41295CFFE02CAEFB6E85C358FF" blockId="4.[170,795,218,2131]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
According to 
<bibRefCitation id="406A90B0295CFFE02D0AFB6E85105B9F" author="Monne, M. A." box="[372,537,1242,1267]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="139 - 144" refId="ref5496" refString="Monne, M. A. 2014. Paracriodion Fragoso (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae, Cerambycinae); redefinition, with description of a new species from Bolivia. Zootaxa, 3847 (1): 139 - 144." type="journal article" year="2014">Monné (2014)</bibRefCitation>
: “ 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02E4FFB6E85B35B9F" authorityName="Fragoso" authorityYear="1982" box="[561,698,1242,1267]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Paracriodion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02E4FFB6E85B35B9F" box="[561,698,1242,1267]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Paracriodion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02DF6FB4E85C15A7F" authority="Martins &amp; Galileo, 2010" authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="2010" box="[392,712,1274,1299]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Iuati" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02DF6FB4E86B15A7F" box="[392,440,1274,1299]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Iuati</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="406A90B0295CFFE02DBFFB4E85C15A7F" author="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M." box="[449,712,1274,1299]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="83 - 90" refId="ref5344" refString="Martins, U. R. &amp; Galileo, M. H. M. 2010. Novas especies, nova sinonimia e novo registro em Cerambycidae (Coleoptera) do Mexico e da America do Sul. Papeis Avulsos de Zoologia, 50 (7): 83 - 90." type="journal article" year="2010">Martins &amp; Galileo, 2010</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
by the unarmed sides of the prothorax and the pronotum with gibbosities and crateriform punctures; in 
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02E07FA8E85A65A3F" box="[633,687,1338,1363]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02E07FA8E85A25A3F" authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="2010" box="[633,683,1338,1363]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Iuati" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Iuati</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
the sides of the prothorax are armed with a prominent median tubercle, and the surface of the pronotum is ornamented with large crateriform punctures, without gibbosities.” Actually, 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02D6BFA0E85435ABF" authority="Fragoso, 1982" authorityName="Fragoso" authorityYear="1982" box="[277,586,1466,1491]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Paracriodion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02D6BFA0E86975ABF" box="[277,414,1466,1491]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Paracriodion</emphasis>
Fragoso, 1982
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02E97FA0E84105ABF" authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="2010" box="[745,793,1466,1491]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Iuati" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02E97FA0E84105ABF" box="[745,793,1466,1491]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Iuati</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only by the antennal tubercles being not nearly contiguous. The crateriform punctures in 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02E63FA4E85AF597F" authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="2010" box="[541,678,1530,1555]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Iuati" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinithorax">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02E63FA4E85AF597F" box="[541,678,1530,1555]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">I. spinithorax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are somewhat variable, and do not differ from those in females of 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02CB7F98E86C3593F" authority="Monne, 2014" authorityName="Monne" authorityYear="2014" box="[201,458,1594,1619]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Paracriodion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morrisi">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02CB7F98E8625593F" box="[201,300,1594,1619]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">P. morrisi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="406A90B0295CFFE02D4AF98E86C3593F" author="Monne, M. A." box="[308,458,1594,1619]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="139 - 144" refId="ref5496" refString="Monne, M. A. 2014. Paracriodion Fragoso (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae, Cerambycinae); redefinition, with description of a new species from Bolivia. Zootaxa, 3847 (1): 139 - 144." type="journal article" year="2014">Monné, 2014</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but the pronotal gibbosities, distinct in 
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02D5FF9EE86B8591F" box="[289,433,1626,1651]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02D5FF9EE86A4591F" authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="2010" box="[289,429,1626,1651]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Iuati" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinithorax">I. spinithorax</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
are very slightly conspicuous in 
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02CD4F9CE863059FF" box="[170,313,1658,1683]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02CD4F9CE863C59FF" authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="2010" box="[170,309,1658,1683]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Iuati" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinithorax">I. spinithorax</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The general appearance of 
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02E18F9CE85FC59FF" box="[614,757,1658,1683]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02E18F9CE85F959FF" authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="2010" box="[614,752,1658,1683]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Iuati" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinithorax">I. spinithorax</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
especially females, is much like that of females of 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02EC7F92E841359DF" authorityName="Monne" authorityYear="2014" box="[697,794,1690,1715]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Paracriodion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morrisi">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02EC7F92E841359DF" box="[697,794,1690,1715]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">P. morrisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(including the shape of the area between antennal tubercles and posterior level of upper eye lobes). However, males of the former have antennae distinctly longer, spiniform projection of the tibiae is shorter in both sexes, distance between upper eye lobes is somewhat smaller, and apex of mesoventral process with lateral tabs (according to 
<bibRefCitation id="406A90B0295CFFE02D5DF8CE86C958FF" author="Monne, M. A." box="[291,448,1914,1939]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="139 - 144" refId="ref5496" refString="Monne, M. A. 2014. Paracriodion Fragoso (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae, Cerambycinae); redefinition, with description of a new species from Bolivia. Zootaxa, 3847 (1): 139 - 144." type="journal article" year="2014">Monné (2014)</bibRefCitation>
, absent in 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02E4AF8CE85B458FF" authorityName="Fragoso" authorityYear="1982" box="[564,701,1914,1939]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Paracriodion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02E4AF8CE85B458FF" box="[564,701,1914,1939]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Paracriodion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2444ED41295CFFE02CAEF82E8689573F" blockId="4.[170,795,218,2131]" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">
The presence or absence of the spiniform lateral tubercle in the prothorax has also been observed in another species of 
<taxonomicName id="E3FB96C2295CFFE02D13F86E85AE589F" authority="Aurivillius, 1912" authorityName="Aurivillius" authorityYear="1912" box="[365,679,2010,2035]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Coleoxestia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="168F3153295CFFE02D13F86E86EE589F" box="[365,487,2010,2035]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="5">Coleoxestia</emphasis>
Aurivillius, 1912
</taxonomicName>
, genus of Sphallotrichina,described as having an unarmed prothorax, although the presence is rare in that genus (
<bibRefCitation id="406A90B0295CFFE02EC8F7AE867F573F" author="Galileo, M. H. M. &amp; Santos-Silva, A." pageId="4" pageNumber="5" pagination="54 - 70" refId="ref5298" refString="Galileo, M. H. M. &amp; Santos-Silva, A. 2016. New taxa, new records and notes on Coleoxestia Aurivillius, 1912 (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae, Cerambycinae). Zootaxa, 4136 (1): 54 - 70." type="journal article" year="2016">Galileo &amp; Santos-Silva, 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
